Navajo Nation

 

Abandoned Uranium Mines

 

    From 1944 to 1986, nearly 30 million tons of uranium ore were extracted from the Navajo Nation for the development of atomic weapons and nuclear power.  The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is partnering with the Navajo Nation and other agencies to address the remaining legacy of uranium mine waste contamination.

 

    This web map displays abandoned uranium mines on and near the Navajo Nation.  The map also provides information about mines that are considered priorities for cleanup, identifies who is the lead on investigation and clean up for these mines, and details the most recent milestone in the Superfund process (i.e. Removal Site Evaluation Completed, etc). Visit our website for more information on EPA efforts with partner agencies to address uranium contamination on Navajo Nation.

 

Using the Map

 Click the Legend icon to view a map key for symbols used.

 Click the Layer List icon to turn on/off data layers being displayed.

 Click the Information icon to learn more about this application

 Click the Basemap Gallery icon to select a different background map.

 Click the Near Me icon to find mines within a buffer from an address or location.

 Click the Print Map icon to print or export a customized map.

 Click the Glossary icon for a list of definitions used in this application.

 

Searching for Mines

The search window allows you to find mines and chapter houses on the map. Start typing to search for mines by Name, Alias, Mine ID, Potentially Responsible Party, Enforcement Action, or Region.

 

The search results will appear below. Click on a result to zoom to that mine on the map.

 

Click on a mine point or polygon in the map to view a pop-up with additional information on the mine. Hover over field names for a definition.

 


Click on the arrow at the bottom of the map to open the Attribute Table. This opens up a table, where you can view mine names and aliases, mine status, potentially responsible parties, acreage, and links to EPA reports on the mine.

 


Mines shown in the Attribute Table can be exported to a comma-separated values (CSV) file.
